Mary Leigh laughed. “The school is running to seed,” she said: “the great men
                        have done all that could be done in the way of beautiful suggestiveness—the
                        little ones can only do suggestiveness of all sorts of vague nastiness which
                        they don’t even understand. But there’s a change coming on in painting;
                        people are beginning to be satisfied with interpreting real nature;
                        and—don’t you think—Anne—a similar change . . .”

“He is a man of the middle ages!” Mrs Spencer would enthusiastically exclaim;
                        “if only we had a few more like him, we should soon build
                        cathedrals and town‐halls like those of the fourteenth century.”
